a land acknowledgment is a simple, powerful way of showing respectand a step toward correcting the stories and practices that erase indigenous peoples history and culture and toward inviting and honoring the truth. acknowledgment by itself is a small gesture. it becomes meaningful when coupled with authentic relationships and informed action. but this beginning can be an opening to greater public consciousness of native sovereignty and cultural rights, a step toward equitable relationship and reconciliation (u.s. department of arts and culturehonor native land guide, 2017)the following video accompanies the usdacs #honornativelanda guide and call-to-action (see the more resources section below) to spread the practice of acknowledgment of traditional native lands at the opening of all public gatherings.office of diversity, equity, and inclusionoffice of the presidentadministration buildingroom 104one washington squaresan jos, ca 95192-0007